<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="163">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Murrill, Lloydia 8: 287 (1946" authorityYear="1945" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma subaustrale" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="subaustrale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">Hebeloma subaustrale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
formed a reasonably well supported clade in the ITS analysis (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. ML topologies with branch support obtained through 1000 replicates of SH-like approximate likelihood ratio tests and ultrafast bootstrap annotated SH-aLRT / ufb at the branches for ≥ 85 % SH-aLRT and ≥ 95 % for ufb support. Collections indicated with * are types; clade names indicated by * include type sequences. Collections in red refer to Mexican material A concatenated ITS, MCM 7 and RPB 2 sequences of Hebeloma sect. Theobromina, rooted with H. sinapizans (H. sect. Sinapizantia) B ITS sequences of H. sect. Naviculospora, rooted with H. islandicum (H. sect. Naviculospora)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.85267.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/708806" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">5B</figureCitation>
), thus it is expected to be identifiable by its barcode. Although the maximum intraspecific distance of the sequences in the analysis is only 0.14%, the minimum distance to other species of the section is 0.7%. At this time (4 Feb 2022), there is no multi-sequence UNITE SH that represents the species; the published sequence of the holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. angustisporium" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="angustisporium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. angustisporium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NR_119890 = HQ179674) formed a singleton SH at the 99% level and the respective SH at the next level included several species.
</paragraph>
